patch:
diff --git a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp
index 268546fe99e1..efd300ab8b48 100644
--- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp
+++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp
@@ -2745,10 +2745,23 @@ public:
       auto *I = cast<Instruction>(V);
       if (!I->getParent())
         continue;
+      // Some instructions may have users that are intentionally ignored (e.g.
+      // during horizontal reduction handling). Pre-mark such users as deleted
+      // and allow them in the assertion below.
+      if (!I->use_empty()) {
+        for (Use &U : I->uses()) {
+          if (auto *UsrI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(U.getUser())) {
+            if (UserIgnoreList && UserIgnoreList->contains(UsrI))
+              DeletedInstructions.insert(UsrI);
+          }
+        }
+      }
       assert((I->use_empty() || all_of(I->uses(),
                                        [&](Use &U) {
-                                         return isDeleted(
-                                             cast<Instruction>(U.getUser()));
+                                         if (auto *UsrI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(U.getUser()))
+                                           return isDeleted(UsrI) ||
+                                                  (UserIgnoreList && UserIgnoreList->contains(UsrI));
+                                         return false;
                                        })) &&
              "trying to erase instruction with users.");
       I->removeFromParent();

reason_thou:
1. Understanding the Issue:
The crash is an assertion failure inside BoUpSLP::removeInstructionsAndOperands asserting that an instruction being erased has no live users or that all its users are already marked deleted. In the provided reproducer, the SLP vectorizer's horizontal-reduction path marks a set of scalar instructions for deletion, but some of their users (like logical and/select chains participating in the reduction) remain live and are not marked deleted. When removeInstructionsAndOperands drops operands and proceeds to remove the instructions from their parent, the assertion triggers because there are still users that are not recognized as deleted.

2. Analyzing opt's Log:
The debug-only log shows SLP vectorization forming bundles for compares and zexts and deciding to vectorize them. Then it collects scalars to remove (RemovedInsts): zexts, compares, and the repeated tobools. It validates users with the condition that each user is either inside the SLP tree, in the UserIgnoreList, or already deleted. This is a diagnostic assertion only. After vectorization, for reduction-specific handling, the code replaces uses of some instructions with poison for users in UserIgnoreList. However, the conditions to do replacement are selective (depend on IE->Idx and other properties). As a result, some users (e.g., logical and/select forming the reduction chain: %2, %4, %7, %5, %8, %11, %12) still reference the scalars scheduled for deletion and are not marked as deleted, which violates the removal-time assertion.
The log confirms the first transformation point is removeInstructionsAndOperands, and the crash occurs right at the assertion that checks users of the to-be-erased instructions.

3. Root Cause Analysis:
removeInstructionsAndOperands assumes that every instruction passed in DeadVals either has no users or all its users have already been marked with DeletedInstructions. This assumption is violated in the horizontal reduction path where RemovedInsts collects scalars, but their users are not consistently marked deleted unless they are vectorized tree nodes or explicitly in the UserIgnoreList and had their uses replaced. In this case, some users are neither deleted nor replaced before we attempt to remove the scalars, triggering the assertion.
This mismatch is specific to the reduction handling: RemovedInsts may include operands (like compares and zexts) used by reduction-chain instructions that are not in RemovedInsts and not yet marked deleted.

4. Proposed Edit Points(s):
We need to make removeInstructionsAndOperands resilient to internal reduction users that are tracked in UserIgnoreList but not yet deleted at this point. Two options exist:
- Eagerly mark users in UserIgnoreList as deleted prior to the assertion.
- Loosen the assertion to treat UserIgnoreList-contained users as logically deleted, since the reduction machinery plans to clean them up later.
A minimal change that preserves existing invariants is to extend the check to accept users in the UserIgnoreList and also pre-mark such instruction users as deleted to keep internal bookkeeping consistent. Insert the following logic just before the assertion in removeInstructionsAndOperands:

At lines 2744-2756 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, add handling to pre-mark users that are in UserIgnoreList as deleted and extend the assertion to allow them:

--- begin edit ---
for (T *V : DeadVals) {
  auto *I = cast<Instruction>(V);
  if (!I->getParent())
    continue;
  // If some users are in the ignore list (e.g. during horizontal reduction),
  // mark them as deleted so the assertion below treats them as internal users.
  if (!I->use_empty() && UserIgnoreList) {
    for (Use &U : I->uses()) {
      if (auto *UsrI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(U.getUser())) {
        if (UserIgnoreList->contains(UsrI))
          DeletedInstructions.insert(UsrI);
      }
    }
  }
  assert((I->use_empty() || all_of(I->uses(), [&](Use &U) {
            if (auto *UsrI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(U.getUser())) {
              return isDeleted(UsrI) || (UserIgnoreList && UserIgnoreList->contains(UsrI));
            }
            return false;
          })) && "trying to erase instruction with users.");
  I->removeFromParent();
  SE->forgetValue(I);
}
--- end edit ---

This change ensures:
- Users internal to the reduction that are being ignored are treated as deleted from the perspective of this removal step.
- The assertion accounts for UserIgnoreList-contained users, preserving the intention of the reduction pipeline where these users will be handled subsequently.

5. Conclusion:
The crash stems from removeInstructionsAndOperands assuming no live users, while horizontal reduction leaves some internal users un-deleted at this point. By pre-marking UserIgnoreList-contained users as deleted and relaxing the assertion to accept them, we align the removal step with the reduction's bookkeeping. This prevents the assertion from firing and maintains internal consistency until the pass completes cleanup. The fix is localized to removeInstructionsAndOperands and should not affect non-reduction paths.

